\frametitle{Conclusion}
\protect\phantomsection\label{conclusion}
COGANT frames codebase analysis as a pipeline from ingestion through a
program graph IR to \textbf{Generalized Notation Notation (GNN)}
exports, with explicit confidence and provenance so that learning
systems can treat analysis noise as data rather than as hidden failure
modes. The Python layer provides session and pipeline APIs, a bundle
abstraction, CLI, review tooling, and HTML reporting; the Rust layer
concentrates graph mechanics and export formatting under crate
boundaries described in \texttt{../cogant/docs/architecture/README.md}.

\begin{block}{Shipped Capabilities}
\protect\phantomsection\label{shipped-capabilities}
Several capabilities ship in the current v0.5.0 release and together
define the behaviour that downstream users can rely on:

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Fixpoint translation engine with 19 real rules.} The shipped
  \texttt{TranslationEngine} re-applies every registered rule on each
  pass, terminates as soon as a pass produces zero new mappings, and
  bounds pathological rule sets with a configurable iteration cap. Each
  iteration boundary is recorded in the internal match log, so
  convergence can be audited after the fact. The packaged rule set under
  \texttt{../cogant/py/cogant/translate/rules/} contains 19 concrete
  \texttt{TranslationRule} subclasses: five structural rules
  (\texttt{ReadOnlyInput}, \texttt{MutatingSubsystem},
  \texttt{Inheritance}, \texttt{Containment}, \texttt{DataPipeline}),
  five semantic rules (\texttt{Observation}, \texttt{Action},
  \texttt{Policy}, \texttt{Preference}, \texttt{Context}), two control
  rules (\texttt{Config}, \texttt{FeatureFlag}), three behavioural rules
  (\texttt{Orchestrator}, \texttt{TestAssertion}, \texttt{EventBus}),
  and four resilience rules (\texttt{RetryPattern},
  \texttt{ErrorBoundary}, \texttt{SingletonAccess},
  \texttt{CircuitBreaker}) --- each a real implementation with
  \texttt{matches()} and \texttt{apply()} bodies rather than a
  placeholder stub.
\item
  \textbf{Rule priority and conflict resolution.} Overlapping mappings
  are reconciled by lexicographic
  \texttt{(rule\_priority,\ confidence\_score)}: when two mappings cover
  overlapping \texttt{graph\_fragment\_node\_ids}, the engine retains
  the larger tuple and records a \texttt{conflict\_resolved} event
  naming the winner, the loser, and the overlap. Most shipped rules use
  the default \texttt{TranslationRule.priority} of \texttt{0};
  \texttt{MutatingSubsystemRule} overrides to \texttt{1} so hidden-state
  evidence wins class-level ties against aggregate \texttt{POLICY} from
  \texttt{InheritanceRule} unless rescoring changes the ordering.
  \texttt{translate\_with\_confidence()} re-scores and re-resolves so
  that confidence-model updates are honoured.
\item
  \textbf{Dynamic enrichment from coverage and traces, wired into the
  default pipeline.} When \texttt{.coverage} SQLite or Cobertura XML
  inputs and Chrome DevTools traces are supplied,
  \texttt{enrich\_graph()} annotates nodes with \texttt{coverage\_hits},
  \texttt{branch\_coverage}, \texttt{call\_count},
  \texttt{avg\_duration\_ms}, and \texttt{is\_hot\_path} metadata, and
  appends \texttt{dynamic\_coverage} and \texttt{dynamic\_trace} markers
  to the program graph's evidence sources. The \texttt{dynamic} stage is
  part of the default pipeline stage list in
  \texttt{cogant/py/cogant/api/pipeline.py}, and the shipped CLI exposes
  a \texttt{-\/-no-dynamic} flag (handled by
  \texttt{PipelineConfig.skip\_dynamic}) for scripted runs that must
  force a purely-static bundle.
\item
  \textbf{Confidence tier promotion.} Mappings whose evidence set
  acquires dynamic markers become eligible for promotion from
  \texttt{STATIC\_ONLY} to \texttt{STATIC\_PLUS\_RUNTIME}, and hot-path
  and branch-coverage metadata raise the underlying score through the
  diversity bonus in Equation \ref{eq:confidence-core}. A purely-static
  run remains a first-class bundle; it is simply marked as such on the
  graph metadata.
\item
  \textbf{Ten-stage pipeline architecture.} The runner executes an
  ordered stage list (\texttt{ingest}, \texttt{static},
  \texttt{normalize}, \texttt{graph}, \texttt{dynamic},
  \texttt{translate}, \texttt{statespace}, \texttt{process},
  \texttt{export}, \texttt{validate}). Stage handlers run inside
  per-stage \texttt{try/except} blocks in \texttt{PipelineRunner.run()}:
  if one stage fails, the error is appended to the bundle and execution
  continues to remaining stages. This produces partial but inspectable
  outputs instead of an immediate pipeline abort.
\item
  \textbf{Complete state-space compilation.} The
  \texttt{StateSpaceCompiler} in
  \texttt{../cogant/py/cogant/statespace/compiler.py} emits
  \texttt{StateVariable}, \texttt{ObservationModality}, \texttt{Action},
  and \texttt{Transition} records directly from the program graph and
  semantic mappings. On the \textbf{6} packaged fixtures every run
  produces a non-empty state-space model, which the
  \texttt{GNNPackageBuilder} then writes out as
  \texttt{state\_space.json}, \texttt{observations.json},
  \texttt{actions.json}, and \texttt{transitions.json} inside the
  canonical \texttt{gnn\_package/} directory.
\item
  \textbf{A/B/C/D matrix derivation.} The \texttt{GNNMatrices} class in
  \texttt{../cogant/py/cogant/gnn/matrices.py} derives the likelihood
  matrix \texttt{A{[}n\_obs\ x\ n\_states{]}}, the transition matrix
  \texttt{B{[}n\_states\ x\ n\_states\ x\ n\_actions{]}}, the preference
  vector \texttt{C} over observations, and the prior \texttt{D} over
  hidden states directly from the compiled state-space and the
  underlying program graph edges. Rows and vectors are normalized to
  valid probability distributions, so the emitted bundle is directly
  compliant with the Active Inference Institute's upstream GNN
  validator.
\item
  \textbf{Principled variational and expected free energy.} The
  functions \texttt{variational\_free\_energy} and
  \texttt{expected\_free\_energy} in
  \texttt{../cogant/py/cogant/simulate/free\_energy.py} operate on the
  derived \texttt{A}/\texttt{B}/\texttt{C}/\texttt{D} matrices and
  implement the canonical Active Inference formulation ---
  \texttt{VFE\ =\ KL{[}Q(s)\ \textbar{}\textbar{}\ P(s){]}\ -\ E\_Q{[}log\ P(o\textbar{}s){]}}
  and
  \texttt{EFE\ =\ sum\ over\ policies\ of\ epistemic\_value\ -\ pragmatic\_value}
  --- rather than the hard-coded scalars used in earlier iterations. The
  \texttt{GNNModelRunner} exercises these functions on every compiled
  bundle during pipeline execution.
\item
  \textbf{Markov blanket extraction with five seed strategies.}
  \texttt{../cogant/py/cogant/markov/blanket.py} partitions nodes into
  internal, sensory, active, and external roles, and
  \texttt{extractor.py} selects seeds via five strategies
  (\texttt{explicit}, \texttt{module}, \texttt{kind}, \texttt{auto} via
  cohesion heuristic, and \texttt{mapping\_kind}). The resulting
  \texttt{markov\_blanket.json} file travels inside every
  \texttt{gnn\_package/} directory and is consumed by the downstream
  Active Inference runner.
\item
  \textbf{Real-world fixture validation.} Beyond the synthetic
  \texttt{control\_positive/} fixtures, the packaged
  \texttt{examples/real\_world/} tree now holds three reductions of
  third-party Python projects (\texttt{flask\_app},
  \texttt{requests\_lib}, and \texttt{json\_stdlib}). The pipeline runs
  end-to-end on all \textbf{6} repositories in under seven seconds each
  on a single macOS workstation (representative wall-clock measurements
  in Section 6), producing a complete 19-file GNN package and a
  100.0/100 validator score on every run; concrete measurements are
  recorded in Section 6.
\item
  \textbf{Forward-reverse-forward round-trip (canonical evaluation
  set).} The v0.5.0 reverse synthesizer now emits POLICY / CONTEXT /
  CONSTRAINT scaffolds proportional to the origin GNN's role counts,
  closing the multiset loss that had kept several uncurated real-world
  targets in the APPROXIMATE or DIVERGENT buckets at v0.4.0. Current
  \texttt{METRICS.yaml} reports \textbf{14} isomorphic, \textbf{6}
  approximate, and \textbf{3} divergent targets (of \textbf{23} total).
  The canonical
  \texttt{cogant/docs/evaluation/ROUNDTRIP\_IMPROVEMENT.md} documents
  the POLICY/CONTEXT fix trajectory; see §9, S01, S02 for tables.
\item
  \textbf{Incremental analysis mode.} The shipped
  \texttt{cogant\ analyze\ -\/-incremental\ \textless{}git-ref\textgreater{}}
  command (and its library form
  \texttt{PipelineConfig.incremental\_since}) re-uses the previous run's
  program graph for unchanged source paths, re-running only the affected
  subgraph. On the Flask benchmark the measured speedups are
  19.6\(\times\) for a no-change invocation and 5.6\(\times\) for a
  single-file change, making COGANT tractable inside per-commit CI loops
  without giving up the rule-based pipeline.
\item
  \textbf{Multi-episode Bayesian learning.}
  \texttt{AgentRuntime.run\_multi\_episode} and \texttt{run\_episode}
  drive Active Inference rollouts over the compiled
  \texttt{gnn\_package/}; the companion
  \texttt{update\_D\_from\_posterior} and
  \texttt{update\_A\_from\_counts} helpers implement Dirichlet /
  count-based posterior updates that let downstream consumers refine the
  prior and likelihood matrices from observed episodes without leaving
  the COGANT runtime.
\item
  \textbf{Production FastAPI server.} \texttt{cogant.server.app} exposes
  \texttt{/health} and \texttt{/translate} endpoints with an integration
  test suite. A packaged \texttt{Dockerfile} (python:3.12-slim + uv,
  \texttt{EXPOSE\ 8080}, curl healthcheck) and
  \texttt{docker-compose.yml} turn the translation pipeline into a
  deployable microservice; this unblocks the P2 target of running COGANT
  as a background service in research-group infrastructure.
\item
  \textbf{Cross-language roundtrip demonstration.} The
  \texttt{examples/zoo/13\_js\_observer} fixture exercises a JavaScript
  observer implementation (with optional \texttt{cogant{[}multilang{]}}
  and an installed grammar) through the forward pipeline, the reverse
  synthesizer, and a full AI cycle, recording a
  \texttt{role\_match\_score} of 1.0 on the forward-reverse-forward
  comparison when that path is enabled. This demonstrates that the
  tree-sitter-backed JavaScript parser plus the language-agnostic
  translation and statespace layers can round-trip a non-Python source
  language on the zoo regression set.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Limitations} follow the honest scope in
\texttt{../cogant/docs/reference/implementation\_status.md}: Python is
first-class; JavaScript/TypeScript require optional
\texttt{cogant{[}multilang{]}} and grammars; additional languages are
largely roadmap; translation rules and state-space extraction remain
\textbf{partial} and repository-dependent (with a long-tail of
domain-specific idioms unaddressed by the 19 shipped rules); native
acceleration is wired only for \texttt{connected\_components} on graph
construction; and the roundtrip result is measured on a
\textbf{23}-target canonical set that is weighted toward curated
fixtures. Users should validate exports on their own corpora before
trusting downstream model metrics.

\textbf{Intended users} include researchers building datasets from
open-source repositories, teams prototyping Active Inference models or
graph neural network training pipelines over program-graph data who need
a single export contract, and engineers extending the system via
\texttt{../cogant/docs/plugins/README.md}.

\textbf{Validation} in the software-engineering sense is split: the
repository's verification report enumerates implemented modules and
entry points; scientific validation of model quality remains the
responsibility of downstream training and evaluation code.
\end{block}

\begin{block}{Roadmap and Future Extensions}
\protect\phantomsection\label{roadmap-and-future-extensions}
Several concrete directions extend the current system. Items already
shipped in v0.2.0 -- v0.5.0 (JavaScript/TypeScript parsing via
\texttt{tree-sitter}, partial Rust acceleration of
\texttt{connected\_components}, incremental re-analysis via
\texttt{cogant\ analyze\ -\/-incremental}) have been removed from this
list and moved into the Shipped Capabilities section above.

\begin{enumerate}
\item
  \textbf{Additional language parsers.} Python ships first-class in
  v0.5.0; JavaScript/TypeScript are available behind optional
  \texttt{cogant{[}multilang{]}} plus grammars. Adding parsers for Java,
  Go, Rust, and C/C++ would cover the majority of remaining open-source
  ML-relevant repositories. Each parser implements the plugin interface
  documented in \texttt{../cogant/docs/plugins/README.md}, so language
  additions do not require changes to the core IR or export pipeline.
  The cross-language round-trip demonstration on
  \texttt{examples/zoo/13\_js\_observer} establishes the template for
  validating new parsers before release.
\item
  \textbf{Broader Rust acceleration.} The v0.5.0 PyO3
  \texttt{connected\_components} FFI demonstrates the template but
  touches only a single graph algorithm. Wiring bindings for the
  remaining hot paths --- rule matching on large
  \texttt{CallGraphBuilder} outputs, Generalized Notation Notation
  section/tensor packing in \texttt{cogant-gnn}, and the
  \texttt{B}-tensor normalisation loops --- would reduce end-to-end
  latency on the largest real-world targets (\texttt{fastapi},
  \texttt{urllib3}) from the current \(\approx 30\,\text{s}\) to
  sub-second timings, based on the Python-vs-Rust microbenchmarks
  committed under \texttt{../cogant/benchmarks/results/}.
\item
  \textbf{LLM-assisted rule discovery.} Translation rules are currently
  hand-authored. A semi-automated workflow could present a large
  language model with unannotated graph fragments and ask it to propose
  candidate rules, which a human reviewer then accepts, edits, or
  rejects via the existing \texttt{ReviewAPI}. This combines the
  pattern-recognition strength of LLMs with the auditability of
  declarative rules; the confidence-tier and provenance-record
  infrastructure already in place gives each LLM-proposed rule a natural
  quarantine state until a human upgrades it.
\item
  \textbf{Cross-repository graph linking.} When multiple repositories
  share interfaces (for example, a library and its consumers), linking
  their program graphs at call boundaries produces a richer training
  signal for tasks such as API misuse detection and cross-project code
  search. The graph homomorphism property defined in Section 2 provides
  the formal basis for identifying shared interface nodes across
  independently analyzed repositories.
\item
  \textbf{Long-tail rule coverage and calibration.} The 19 shipped
  translation rules carry deliberate \texttt{TODO(calibration)} markers
  for confidence-threshold tuning (see
  \texttt{cogant/py/cogant/translate/confidence.py} and
  \texttt{cogant/py/cogant/statespace/variables.py}). A 20+ repository
  gold-standard corpus, annotated by human reviewers through the
  \texttt{ReviewAPI}, would turn those principled defaults into
  empirically validated thresholds and surface the long-tail idioms that
  the current rule families miss.
\end{enumerate}
\end{block}
